Story time....



I've seen a pattern across PE investment thesis for AI companies. The deals evaluate the strength of AI value creation, revenue models, IP etc; rightfully so. The integration plan almost never includes AI accountability infrastructure.

Unit economics is what makes the ROI real and defensible. Most PE firms miss this in their due-diligence, build it in from the start by bringing the right AI due diligence expertise.



This was true for a recent proposal I vetted. Solid IP developed over 5+ years. Vast market application, solving issues laterally across industries - Blockchain, Healthcare, Retail - the sky was the limit for expansion. The kind that VCs shy away from but PEs have built up an appetite for.



During my due diligence the product worked beautifully with promising scalability but the proposal missed defensibility of their revenue model. The ARR worked on paper but when looked under the hood, even with aggressive GTM, scaling cost compression was nowhere close. What did this mean? AI companies are hung up on product-fit, they miss the pathways that generate higher revenue that requires grunt work for market-fit & architectural scalability without resource chokeholds.



How I approach my due diligence:

- Stress-test revenue projections.

- Scale cost compression against an over fetching AI model.

- Viability of ARR growth targets.

- Capitalization of AI resources post-close.



AI models without proper due-diligence become capital locked investments for PE firms. My recommendation in the above scenario was not to kill the deal but give the team 90-days to rearchitect with proper inference caching, restructure the prompting layer followed by baseline architecture improvements reported back to the PE firm Bi-Weekly. 



